04827nam a22006135i 9780822382744DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t19971997ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223827447 a10.1515/97808223827442doi  a(DE-B1597)554653  a(OCoLC)1125522962  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHD6073.C62bF734 1997 7aBUS0000002bisacsh04a331.4/887/0944362201 aGreen, Nancy L., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aReady-to-Wear and Ready-to-Work :bA Century of Industry and Immigrants in Paris and New York /cNancy L. Green; Andrew Gordon, Daniel James, Alexander Keyssar. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[1997] 4cÂ©1997  a1 online resource (446 p.) :b10 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aComparative and international working-class history00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tI Fashion as Industry -- t1 Fashion and Flexibility: The Garment Industry between Haute Couture and Jeans -- t2 Seventh Avenue -- t3 The Sentier -- t4 Bermuda Shorts in Comparative Perspective -- tII The Social Consequences of Flexibility -- t5 The Sweatshop as Workplace and Metaphor -- t6 Women, Immigrants, and Skill in the Garment Shops -- t7 "An Industry of Passage": The Immigrant Waves -- t8 Conflict and Consensus on Seventh Avenue -- t9 Economic and Ethnic Identities in the Parisian Patchwork -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNancy L. Green offers a critical and lively look at New York's Seventh Avenue and the Parisian Sentier in this first comparative study of the two historical centers of the women's garment industry. Torn between mass production and "art," this industry is one of the few manufactauring sectors left in the service-centered cities of today. Ready-to-Wear and Ready-to-Work tells the story of urban growth, the politics of labor, and the relationships among the many immigrant groups who have come to work the sewing machines over the last century.Green focuses on issues of fashion and fabrication as they involve both the production and consumption of clothing. Traditionally, much of the urban garment industry has been organized around small workshops and flexible homework, and Green emphasizes the effect this labor organization had on the men and mostly women who have sewn the garments. Whether considering the immigrant Jews, Italians, Puerto Ricans, Dominicans, and Chinese in New York or the Chinese-Cambodians, Turks, Armenians, and Russian, Polish, and Tunisian Jews in Paris, she outlines similarities of social experience in the shops and the unions, while allowing the voices of the workers, in all their diversity to be heard.A provocative examination of gender and ethnicity, historical conflict and consensus, and notions of class and cultural difference, Ready-to-Wear and Ready-to-Work breaks new ground in the methodology of comparative history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aWomen clothing workerszFrancezParisxHistory. 0aWomen clothing workerszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 0aWomen foreign workerszFrancezParisxHistory. 0aWomen foreign workerszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / General.2bisacsh1 aGordon, Andrew, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aJames, Daniel, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKeyssar, Alexander, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK Archive eBook-Package 1964-1999z978311071360240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822382744zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/